,Recommended,313630,25214497,"Posted: 28 August, 2016",all,genoforprez,"Holy sh** this game is captivating. All the negative reviews are from VR kids who don't like the VR implementation. If you don't care about VR, then there is no reason not to buy this. Absolutely worth the full $20.It's a survival game, but there are more things to be mindful of than in most survival games. Ways you can fail to survive include:--Starvation--Dehydration--Hypothermia--Overheating--Exhaustion (lack of sleep)--Physical damage to body (falling, etc)The game makes all of these even more challening by putting you on a planet with volatile temperature and weather conditions. One minute the temperature is below freezing so you have to huddle in a cave throwing sticks on a fire while waiting for the cold front to pass, then the next minute it's blistering hot so that you have to run from shade to shade to keep your body temp from rising too high. And of course you have to stay on top of food and water.Unlike other survival games, there is no farming---only gathering. And there is technically no storage, although you can still hoarde piles of things because the game will remember where you dropped them.Also unlike other survival games, there is a narrative and an overarching goal to this game. It's not just a game of seeing how long you can survive---you're also trying to scavenge materials from crash sites to build a satellite uplink. There are also huge caves and dungeons to explore (be sure to bring food, water, and light!)---not to mention loads of secret items as exploration rewards.If you like survival gameplay but also like exploring and having a definite end goal, then this game is worth every cent.I emphasize again that this review pertains to the regular, non-VR experience.*edit*Updating this review because it's also worth noting the following:--This is first and foremost an adventure/exploration game, but there are some survival elements as described above. HOWEVER. The game lets you tweak the survival settings to make them more intense or, if you prefer, make them completely negligible so you can focus on just the exploration (which is also fantastic!). So FYI if you like exploring but dislike survival.--By default the game uses the metric system. But if you were born in stubborn America, like me, then the game options can be tweaked to use Fahrenheit / ounces / miles / etc.--By default the protagonist is male, but you can switch to a female voice in options (mostly just your typical grunts and groans, but the protagonist DOES talk occasionally, so take your preference).*/edit*7) A classic, essential, and/or must-buy game that is worth full price.6) A good game that is worth the full price.5) A pretty good game worth checking out--especially if discounted.4) A fairly good game, but I'd recommend buying it discounted.3) Not great, but a few redeeming qualities. Only buy if heavily discounted.2) Only worth checking out if you are dangerously curious.1) Avoid at all costs."
,Not Recommended,313630,23480702,"Posted: 10 June, 2016",all,Tenko,"The Solus Project is too simplistic to be a survival game, too easy to be an old-school adventure game, and too linear and dull to be an exploration game.Survival elements in the game are so dumbed down, they're pointless. Your character doesn't starve or dehydrate as quickly as actual survival games and you have easy access to unlimited food and water at frequent resting spots throughout the game, and other food/water items are easy enough to find anyways. Crafting is extremely limited, with too few items and combinations. Surviving the planet's climate extremes is marginally better, but you spend the majority of the game underground in low temperatures, and you get access to a heating ball fairly early on that renders most of the surviving parts irrelevant.The game's attempt at 'puzzles' is laughably poor. They are either (1) find key to stick in lock/device, (2) put rocks on pressure plates to open door, (3) step on/operate mechanism to select clearly-marked symbol, and if we're being really generous, (4) press button to open door. None of these would ever count as real puzzles in any other game, but this is the best The Solus Project can do. Clearly, this was meant to be the spiritual successor to developer's previous game The Ball only because it involves giant metal spheres as plot devices.And finally, the exploration is limited. You start on a very small island with terrain that, while not completely impassable, locks you into only a handful of paths, most of which just lead you to the single cave/ladder entrance to the island's underground. From there it's a single underground path to travel through, hitting the occasional large space that, again, has a single entrance and single exit, any number of the previously-mentioned non-puzzles, and then you hit the loading screen that takes you to the next island, where you do it all over again. In theory, you can try and wander everywhere to find the secrets the game keeps count of. You could just pull out the teleporter and squeeze yourself into every nook and cranny, or start jumping around the rocks to get places, but what's the point? The secrets you find are items that boost your survival stats, but the survival gameplay as described earlier is completely pointless.And it's not like the setting and story are interesting enough to explore, either. You're basically just walking through the same-old tunnels to find just different varieties of underground temples with different collections of skeletons inside. You figure there would be an interesting story to them, but The Solus Project also falls apart here. The game's only way of communicating is to make you read exposition from these giant stone tablets that your tricorder-like Wilson device translates for you. It's clunky and uninteresting, and you quickly get bored of stopping to read everything.Overall, The Solus Project is a terrible game. If you want a survival game, go buy a real survival game. If you want an adventure game, get one with actual puzzles. If you want something with an interesting world to explore, there are a ton of other options that aren't even open-world. Whatever it is you want, The Solus Project isn't it. Save your money and your time."
76561198117691736,Recommended,313630,28084753,"Posted: 29 November, 2016",all,RyerStar,"You wake up to a foreign sky. The moment you step out you are greeted by a meteor rain or a closing tornado. You turn around and you see an ominous planet just over the horizon.Welcome to Gliese, the mysterious planet on which the Solus Project takes place.The game is described as an advanced environmental survival-exploration game with very mild horror elements. And it's just that. You walk/run around looking for clues to what happened to the other ships from the expedition trying to survive as the planet isn't very friendly – the weather changes from heat to chill, heavy rains, meteor showers, tornadoes may occur instantly and you better run for cover. There are a lot of documents, diaries, photos scattered around and by reading them the player starts learning about the Solus Project and what caused it.At its core the game is a walking simulator, there are very few hostile creatures and your main concern should be looking for food and water and surviving the climate changes, you have no firearms just a teleporting device. And here is where the main problem lies IMO. Most of the time you have to babysit the survivor. Especially annoying is that he gets tired and needs to sleep every 10-15min even after sleeping for 8hrs on a mattress and a pillow. You start exploring an area, tornado/meteors/heavy rains interrupt your exploration, you have to look for cover and wait for the weather to stabilize. Finally you go exploring again and just after a few steps you hear “Operator tired, sleep advised”. You can choose to ignore it but the suit AI won't stop repeating it every 60sec. Or “Operator wet and cold, temperature dropping”. OMG, is the “operator” a trained interstellar explorer or just a boyscout-wanna-be?Aside from that, The Solus Project is a nice exploration game. It has good graphics, interesting story, no bugs or any other setbacks. If you are into stories, exploration, loneliness – this game is for you."
,Recommended,313630,24444577,"Posted: 21 July, 2016",all,ℛᵸᵞᵗᵸᵐᶳ ♫,"This game was suggested for me by my Steam Queue, and by the trailer alone I knew this was my kind of game. Gladly I wasn’t wrong. I am a big sucker for Sci-fi stories, and very recently I have been finding out I’m a fan of survival games. This game is a delightful mix of both elements.I have to mention that the Story part is stronger than the survival one, but just one bit. This, however was no problem for me, since I enjoy a good story. And this game kept me on the edge of my seat while I was figuring out what happened in the planet I crashed into.Talking about the planet, the atmosphere of the game is amazing, climate is always changing and even when most of this changes are dangerous for you, are still a sight to behold. This is one of the things this game doesn’t lack, great visuals enhanced even more by a great use of soundtrack and sfx’s.Now, there is a horror-survival side of this game, however I wouldn’t call it much “horror” as it is creepy, which at least in my opinion, it’s 10 times better. Because the times you can get scared in this game does not rely on cheap jump-scares. But in its ability to keep you “uncomfortable” in an environment that you are not familiar with, and why would you? It is an alien planet after all!This element of the game intensifies as you get deeper into the dark caves and unveil secrets which I won’t spoil any further!--There is however, an issue that it’s worth mention for AMD Fx users such as me. Apparently there is a “hiccup” with this processor and the audio used for this engine (Unreal 4) which causes the game to freeze at some points when the game is loading. Which is obviously a minor inconvenience.That being said, I can testify the devs have been working hard to find out the source of this problem and facilitated a patch for us AMD fx users, which can easily be found in the discussion forums.--Anyway, even with all that, I still recommend this game because you can tell how much work was put into it. One of my best gaming experiences in the latest years.And an even stronger recommendation if you are Sci-fi fan like me.Pros:- Engaging story- Great use of visuals, sound and music- Lots of secrets to discover- Big areas to wander around and exploreCons:- Audio glitches (for AMD Fx)- Survival can get a little too easy some of the times (For hardcore survival players)"
