76561197985887185,Recommended,313630,23485149,"Posted: 10 June, 2016",all,Stian,"I love this game on the Vive. It's probably my favourite experience on the device so far, after having bought about 50 games. And that from a game with VR support added after the game was mostly done. That of course has its limitations. The inventory is cumbersome (but l understand the devs are working on it), and the controls aren't always logical. You have to push a button to interact with things (that is probably hard to fix as the game is designed around a controller). But you can use your hands independently, light your way with the torch etc. and move about freely. The default locomotion will be tough for some, but with a little tinkering you can adjust the walk speed, and even make the in game clock slower so you have more time to explore the incredible looking locations.  You even get a teleportation gun you can use for moving around if your VR legs isn't good (I haven't used it much though as I find the default locomotion very nice, but I've had some time to train my VR legs). It can be quite scary in VR, with an eary atmosphere, and I have more than once had chills go down my spine.And the story so far is really good, keeps me pushing on. This game is fantastic! The VR implementation is an example for other devs to follow, and its improving with every update. Thank you devs for giving me this amazing experience in VR!"
76561198051362289,Recommended,313630,28214054,"Posted: 5 December, 2016",all,foaminator,"Good Exploration Game with a StoryThe Solus Project is a good exploration game with a touch of survival threaded together by an interesting story. I played entirely in 2D (no VR) and it never felt like a tech demo. I played almost a full 40 hours before reaching the end. I could have gone longer if I explored more, but I felt like it was a good time to end.Do's and Don'tsDo expect to deal with varying degrees of threatening environmentsDon't expect any combat; you can't even swat a flyDo expect to search for food and water and safe places to sleepDon't expect a lot of crafting; the recipes are mostly just combining two itemsDo play with the game audio on. The audio is cool and audio cues are extremely helpful.Things that could be ImprovedYou can only hold one thing at a time which is annoying when you need one item for your environment (e.g. a light or temperature control item) and another to do an actionSome of the areas with extremely high and extremely low temperatures are more of a pain than a survival mechanic. Towards the end, even with the best possible items, there were times I had to drop a bunch of items to create a ""temperature offset zone"" just so I could bring my body temperate up/down.You can only hold items in your right hand. Generally this doesn't matter, but when going for high precision shots with the Teleporter, you can get ""locked out"" of a shot that would be possible with your left hand.To get the max distance on the Teleporter, you have to jump. Since you can only hold the Teleporter and nothing else, this just delays how long it takes to get a good shot. Plus, it just feels stupid.Sprinting is interrupted by jumping or short steps down. So long as you hold down the sprint button, you should be sprinting regardless of your other actions or terrain.There's a bit too much crouching required. It's painfully slow and despite the reality that dank caves would require a lot of crouching, it just slows down the exploration.The stuttering of walking up stairs is far slower than walking up the railing beside it. I understand that's more realistic, but I shouldn't hate stairs and constantly seek out a railing to move around the game world.There were very few glitches and they were minor or brief. A short period of no rain sounds while standing in rain or a little terrain flicker in a corner. It's a solid game that has a lot to offer, especially for the price. I think it's worth full price, but if you find it on sale, it's a must buy."
76561197983163896,Recommended,313630,28469557,"Posted: 19 December, 2016",all,BeatYourHeadIn,"Non-VR reviewThe Solus Project is one of those indie creations to get excited about. It’s a very good game, but is it a perfect game? Of course not! It’s got a few weird things going on: a couple graphical issues and seemingly endless references to other intellectual properties (borrows much from TV show Lost in particular). Readers, I know what you’re thinking: So what, another indie studio created another indie game blah blah blah why should I care? Readers, I already told you the answer to that: it’s a very good game! Weren’t you listening!? Think: a crispy Lost pie crust with the disappointing conclusion trimmed off (Season 6, I’m looking at you) and fill that with Interstellar custard cream, but now scrape the oily Matt Damon meringue off the top and then sprinkle with a couple teaspoons of crushed Ancient Aliens. Ahhhh, pure heaven I tell ya!Okay, so there’s no black hole or time travel in TSP, but it captures that “Interstellar” vibe nonetheless. More than once, I found myself overlooking an alien tropical beach paradise at the precipice of a craggy drop off and wanting pump both fists into the air and yell, “I’M THE MATTHEW MCCONAU♥♥♥♥ OF THE WORLD!!!” I didn’t though. My wife isn’t into videogames. Such spontaneous outbursts would be frowned upon and followed up by punishment nagging to do irrelevant tasks. Yeah, fetching that glass of water for you and then that bowl of kale chips for you and then turning off that hallway light so you could watch Gilmore Girls without the glare sure showed me for enjoying something without you. Lesson learned.Ahem, moving on readers, this is simulated walking at its finest. That statement is coming from me: a gamer who loathes Dear Esther et al. I feel like TSP goes the extra mile to stand apart in its genre, so much so that “Exploration Simulator” would be a more accurate description of TSP’s gameplay.Exploration of the unknown carries the risk of fatal failure. If history is a guide, then it has shown us that the cost of expeditions to parts unknown is paid not only in coin, but often in blood as well. Elon Musk knows this when he asks “are you prepared to die” on a journey to Mars? In a game that tries to put explorers on Gliese-6143-C, a fictional planet orbiting another star, you can bank on people dying in it. Spoiler alert: they do!Exploration of the treacherous unknown is all well and good. Eventually though, the unknown becomes the known, the traps and pitfalls mapped and accounted for, yada yada yada fartnoise. That’s a problem when the main hook is exploring; before long, the soul-sucking boredom of the type found in standard walking simulators can seep in. Worry not readers, for the agile TSP parries the creeping tectonic blow of boredom with a quick megathrust of excellent pacing. You are encouraged onward via objectives at a rate slow enough to let you take in the sights of the superbly crafted islands and caves, while fast enough to keep the flow moving forward. If you linger, it’s at your choosing and likely because you are trying to find the secret areas, you elite completionist, you.In that sense, despite the open world that allows backtracking and travel between areas at will, TSP is a linear game with a defined beginning, middle and end. This structure keeps things fresh hour after hour, much like those packets of silica beads found in packaged products (you know, the ones that say “DO NOT EAT”? I really should start listening to those warnings). However, I did experience some game fatigue, but that was after 35 friggin’ hours in a 16 hour game, so yeah my fault mostly. Fortunately, getting back into the plot progression quickly reengaged my interest.The plot is solid in TSP. It is a chunky mishmash of other sources but it injects originality into the mix. In the 22nd century, a rogue star has destroyed Earth and torn asunder most of the solar system; a cataclysm that has stranded the survivors with dwindling supplies on ark ships near Pluto. Before they can burn fuel reserves needed to leave the shattered remnants of the Sol System behind, they must desperately await the “all clear to colonize” signal from any of the scout vessels sent to promising exoplanets. Wow, that’s just the backstory.I’m on a scout ship lightyears away, which suddenly turns into a roman space candle while entering orbit around an exoplanet. All of my crewmates appear to die in the explosion. That’s okay though, I could use a little alone time after spending 8 years pent up with them inside that relativistic sardine can. So there I am, crash landed and alone, and loving it!All kidding aside, the atmosphere from then on is tragically hopeful as I realize I can still succeed in my scout mission if I collect enough scrapped spaceship parts to build a transmitter. I cling to that shard of positive thinking, which the plotline sinisterly whittles away at as if it were carving a marshmallow roasting stick. I soon felt that at some point I would be plunged into the fire. The survival of mankind hinged on my ability to overcome creeping hopelessness. This is a story that I thoroughly enjoyed, and I found the emotionally charged conclusion to it very satisfying.This is a story supported by strong visual and audio production. The graphics are excellent, with a couple of issues. There is a weird distortion effect sometimes seen on the edges of objects that are framed in the near background by water. Also, on my midrange system with the settings on Ultra, 1080p ran at 60fps+ but dropped inexplicably every couple of hours to 40ish until I entered a loading screen or restarted the game. Not a game breaker for me; it simply meant that I had to play a small percentage of the game below the ideal framerate. Besides, the audio steals the show here, readers.The sounds of Gliese-6143-C pull you into the fantasy. From the thematic background music to the immersive ambience, you can hear the love that Teotl put into this important aspect to gaming that is too often overlooked by other dev teams. My biggest complaint here is the voice acting. If your preferred language is English DO NOT PLAY THIS GAME AS THE MALE CHARACTER! The guy who voiced the male derped hard and cannot sell the story. Luckily, the woman who voiced the female protagonist did an incredible job capturing the emotion behind the script. I smiled her smiles, shivered her shivers, and cried her tears (they were crocodile tears, no wetness; manhood=restored). Play with the female voice enabled or don’t play it at all. Yeah it’s that important to the journey through TSP.To aid that journey, you scavenge supplies from ship wreckage and derelict alien settlements and craft various inventory and quest items. Scavenging is crucial, but this game mechanic is well implemented and avoids the tedious resource grind found in other open world survival games. For example, you don’t need to stock up excessively on food; you could live almost entirely off of the infinite alien food and water stations found around the levels. The devs took the infinite supplies idea a little too far, though. Alien technology explains infinite food stations, but the oily bark torches you craft that never burn out was a weird design decision. After you craft the first torch, there’s no need to make another one. Small gripe I know.That’s how well TSP is made; I’m nitpicking to find things I didn’t like. More nitpicking: the exploitable loophole where you can put a burning torch in the inventory “backpack” and submerge yourself in water, then get out and pull the still burning torch out of the backpack… then use it to help dry yourself off. Come on Teotl, that’s dumb. The torch system should be reworked for more realism. Again, nitpicking.TSP is a well-crafted adventure. A must play for sci-fi fans.TL;DR this game is a steal at $20. I got it for 10 and I’ve been indicted for internet piracy."
