,Recommended,313630,21401588,"Posted: 23 February, 2016",all,Emeritus,"The Solus Project is an exploration game (walking simulator) with great atmosphere and some survival elements. It's not an open world game with resources and crafting, the levels are linear and there is plenty of alien guacamole and water in the tombs, so you won't have to worry much about survival (except for when random tornado/meteor shower catches you on planet surface).But if you like story driven exploration games with mysteries, this one is the best looking atmospheric sci-fi ""the interstellar like"" experience you can get for 4 euros xD"
,Recommended,313630,25517604,"Posted: 15 September, 2016",all,buffaloseven,"The Solus Project is a hybrid adventure/survival game, successfully melding environmental exploration with managing the hazards an alien world. What begins as a fairly straightforward ""crashed on an alien planet, time to survive and find out what happened"" quickly evolves into a larger mystery uncovered through environmental storytelling and glyphs left around the environment.The game does a wonderfully job of making you feel like you're exploring an alien world; one that's familliar yet not quite right. The general atmosphere of the game is fairly benign, save for a stretch of time in the middle of the game where it shifts into more of a thriller/horror setting. It wasn't something I was expecting, which made it all the more unsettling (which I believe was the intended reaction).Puzzle solving is fairly intuitive and melds well with the exploration focus.  The survival elements never became overbearing. The storytelling was delivered well and I enjoyed piecing things together and constructing a fuller understanding of what happened to my ship and what exactly has happened on the world you're stranded on. The ending stumbles a little bit, of which your understanding of it will likely depend on how many pieces of lore you've uncovered and how well you've stitched it together in your head. I could see the ending making little to no sense for people who just main-line it straight through; finding ways to make some of the more important historical information central to the main progression would have smoothed over this issue.The game looks gorgeous with numerous times where I just stopped to take in the scenery. Unreal Engine 4 runs great and I experienced no crashes or bugs. I did not play in VR.All in all, The Solus Project is a great little game that will take you around 10-15 hours to beat and offers an interesting story, unique and compelling world, and plenty of pretties to make your eyeballs happy. Recommended."
,Recommended,313630,23420320,"Posted: 6 June, 2016",all,Nubby Ninja,"Solus, where to start.The direction of the game is a unique one. You are one of the last humans alive in the universe. You crash land on an alien beach (ARK) and have to use basic crafting supplies to survive (ARK). As you progress alien sounds and relics empower and guide your path to find a benevolent intelligence at work.The strengths of this game include a bizarre alien weather system, which makes survival interesting and unpredictable. One minute you're burning hot, the next you're freezing. You can retreat to various safe areas, which typically coincide with save points, but you will encounter a dark presence, which leaves you few options for a safe retreat.As survival games go, this one has puzzles that remind me strongly of any of the recent Metroid games. (I say recent, I think back to Gamecube and Nintendo 64) The puzzles require intelligence and planning. You will eventually have more locks than keys. Choose wisely! (spoiler)The textures (graphics) leave a little to be desired, but as you go you get swept up in the big picture. There are very few glitches (if any, I have encountered none) and many hours to be derived between searching for secrets, dodging the weather, hunting for aliens, and finding interesting new things to craft.This game gets 5/5 from me. Definitely recommended."
76561197971787986,Recommended,313630,30932614,Posted: 3 April,all,pro-zak,"Highly recommended for explorers and completionists. This game is hours and hours of exploring, walking around vast cave and tunnel networks, temples, and deserted-ish islands. If you just want to wander 'over this way' and see what's there, you're going to probably enjoy this game. There are secrets to be found, journals and labels to read, inventory to keep track of ... all the while keeping yourself healthy (warm, fed, rested).It's not 100% free-roam, happy-go-lucky: there are a few antogonists you'll have to learn to avoid or run from. The first few times I encountered these things, I was swearing and messing my drawers, as the makers of this fantastic game outdid themselves with the music score. Dread and anxiety, heh ... why not just say FEAR, crept up on me as the music & sounds got closer. It's not horror genre, however. There are no jump-scares or zombies out to dine on your flesh. After a few run-ins with the 'things', you'll learn how to properly deal with them, and (hopefully as I did) marvel at their presence.There are puzzles, jumping puzzles. Nothing hard and annoying, especially since one of your tools allows you to go pretty much ANYWHERE you want to.The game is LONG, and replayable. I found less than half of the secrets, and look forward in a few years time to hitting it up again with someone's video/guide/map to aid me in finding every nook & cranny."
