76561198036943999,Recommended,313630,34382348,Posted: 20 August,all,SamuraiJones,"Wonderful vision for a game. Mediocre implementation. Great story in a complex world, marred by trivial difficulty and some technical struggles. The game looks like it may be intended for VR, but I played with an old-fashioned flatscreen and controller, and it worked out fine.So the premise is a survival game where you're stranded on an alien world. You explore derelict alien ruins, read ancient texts about the aliens and their gods, manipulate machinery to access different parts of the world through a series of caves. You have to contend with hunger and thirst, but also heat/cold and violent weather. Meteor storms, tornados, hail, and even rain can be an obsticle if you're unprepared. As you play through, you collect alien artifacts that increase your stats. Your ultimate goal is collecting parts to reestablish communications with the human race, but there's plenty of secrets and flavor text to find to add context to the world.The game basically has two environments. You spend time on islands, which represent small, encapuslated open-world-esque environments where you have to explore and scavange. You also spend a fair amount of time in caves/underground ruins, which still take some exploring, but are much more linear than the islands. Finding food and water is still a concern underground, but the environment is much less hostile and the temperature more stable. There are traps, but they're pretty easy to avoid.The game does a good job of building a story from fragments of text. Records chiselled in stone by one of the alien factions, or your crew's journals or notes, discovered in ship wreckage. You learn about the aliens and their history, and about what has happened on earth. Occasionally, you'll be able to receive a message from the humans back home updating you on the direness of their situation. They do a great job of constructing an interesting and ominous story.There's plenty of in-game creepy stuff, not all of which makes much sense. As the game advances, you occasionally will catch glimpses of ""something"" in the distance in a cave, or on the horizon. There are creepy encounters where corpses will sit up and watch you as you move past. Creepy fun, but not all of it fits with rest of the story. I justified it by saying that besides the alien stuff going on, but the survivor is also going a little crazy from the isolation.Visually the game is great, but not very diverse. The environment all looks the same. There's maybe 4 or 5 types of plants, and aside from the few important alien structures, there's a few generic looking buildings and a few statues that keep popping up. All the islands look the same. A few have a different terrain -- a series of tiny islands connected by bridges or a hard-to-navigate mountain sticking out of the ocean -- and while you have to deal with the enviroment differently, they manage to all look identcal to the last. Caves are slightly more visually diverse, with lava and ice caves appearing later, but it soon becomes routine. The game is visually striking at first, but becomes a bit of an eyesore by the end.There are a few technical difficulties with the game. I didn't see any bugs per-say, but the framerate was terribly unstable. There were a few times it would be in the 60s, and there were a few times it was probably closer to 20. I would guess it hung around 25-30 for most of the game. My PC plays most modern games just fine, but these small-name companies sometimes skimp on optomization I think, because the video loading seems much higher than the graphics would justify. The frame rate didn't seem to really match up with the complexity of the environment either. A cave with two or three lights at a time, and a 20 foot field of vision: 25fps. You get out of the cave and get onto an island with lots of structures and shadows, a sky, and miles of visual field, and suddenly the frame rate jumps to 60. Also, the game does have an explicit load-screen that you have to wait through between areas... nothing wildly long, but it's been a while since I played a game that required that.The gameplay itself was probably the weakest point of this game. It was easy. So crazy, ridiculously easy that it was boring. I get on the first island, and it looks like consumables don't regenerate, and at first i'm worried. I start collecting resources in the first cave-shelter, slowly stumbling through creating of basical tools like a torch and fire, banging rocks together to make cutting implements to open the food cans. It's looking like a hard-core survival game.As I explore, I notice I'm close to the objective marker, so I take a look at it. Now I'm in a cave which leads me from the first island to the second. As I'm going through the cave, there's green alien food everywhere. Far more than I need or can carry, so I'm leaving most of it behind. When I arrive at the second island, I find a cave another survivor had inhabitted, with his whole stockpile of food, including a lighter (fits in inventory, and has unlimited uses), a sword, a solar-powered flashlight. Guess I don't really need those basic tools anymore. Ok, so now I'm exploring the second island, which is littered with food-cans and refillable water-bottles from the ship. I find a pot of ""alien stew"" which provides endless food.Anyway, I could keep going, but the short version is that before long, I was carrying very little food, because there was so much scattered around, I could always eat from the environment instead of my inventory. I carried 2 waterbottles through most of the game, both of which I found on the first island. When exploring, there were enough endless-food stewpots that I could live indefinately almost anywhere in the world. Torches never ran out, so I only made one and it provided 90% of my light and heat needs through the game. There were always heat and cold sources in the environment, so I never carried any materials for fire (there was a brief time in the first ice-cave where I carried some fire-materials, but soon I constructed an alien heat-orb, so I never had to make that fire). There were a few times I had to explicitly focus on survival, but most of the time it was so easy it was more tedious than challenging.So I guess my summery is that the game does a great job of telling an epic tale of human struggle against a hostile world, discovering a mysterious alien history -- although most of it the story is in note fragments, so it feels more like Myst than Telltale Games. In terms of gameplay and visuals, it starts of interesting, but very quickly becomes dull and repetative.If exploring an alien world sounds interesting, don't let the slow gameplay deter you, because I think you'll be satisfied. I've played plenty of ""walking simulator"" games that were an absolute chore to finish, and this is much more engaging. On the other hand, if you're looking for hardcore survival, or a fast-paced character driven story, you'd probably be better off with something else."
