,Recommended,313630,26641676,"Posted: 17 November, 2016",all,Megakoresh,"Solus project is a story-focused exploration game with survival elements.The story of this game is mostly told through environmental storytelling: reading plaques scatterd through the environment, observing said environment, listening to the protagonist recording his diary and some communication from the rest of the humanity's fleet. This game is quite good at storytelling, much better than I would have expected from this studio, given The Ball's... questionable storyline, both in terms of delivery and writing. This one's story is not only fantastically voice-acted (albiet there is VERY little dialogue), the environments are also excellently crafted and paced to preserve the sense of mystery, without creating confusion.Game's world is scattered though several open levels, which you progress between in a linear fashion (though you can always go back to explore and scavenge a previous level). Levels are rather open at the start and they get more linear toward the end. I don't know why it was made this way, it doesn't detract anything from the experience, but it doesn't add anything either. And sometimes I did miss a little storyline-free exploration towards the end of the game. Closer to the end you start to get a lot of information very rapidly, making a little more open and safe to explore levels would have helped some people process that info, IMO.Throughout the game, as you explore you are required to manage a basic set of survival stats. That is probably the most frustrating thing in the game, and for the most part it serves no purpose other than to restrict you from exploring at your own pace. Thankfully the survival elements are rather simplistic and not the focus (and by setting difficulty to easy you can pretty much just ignore them), because if they weren't I would definitely have hated this game. As it stands, they simply get in the way, but not too much.What I will say is that there is a stat which DOES contribute to gameplay: temperature. Manging temperature in this game is closely tied to gameplay, and unlike other survival stats, it actually contributes a lot to the atmosphere in some places. Reminds me of Cryostasis: Sleep of Reason (maker's breath, that was a good game), except here you also need make sure you don't overheat, just as much as freeze.This game does let you save your progress at any time by sleeping (assuming you sleep in a safe place), which is very important as it is incredibly unfair, when it comes to killing you. Most of the dangers in this game come from hazards, and there is one in particular - some sort of alien drone, that they don't actually reveal the details about, which kills you instantly when it touches you. That drone has fixed paths it partols, but instead of going back and forth like you'd expect, it spawns at the start of the path after finishing the route. When you don't know where that start is, it can and it WILL spawn right on you, killing you instantly. That would be incredibly infuriating if you could only save at save shrines. As it stands it's just a mild annoyance. The game also likes to obsure some traps in shadows, and there's a hazard which instantly kills you when you walk into with a torch lit (this is not mentioned ever before). Furthermore the game can spawn climate anomalies, which you have to hide from in caves, however especially towards the end of the game, the caves are really not that common, so if you encounter such an anomaly and you don't find any shelter in the next 30 seconds (which depends largely on luck), you are also dead.One of the greatest things about this game is it's sound design. Fantastic ambiance, with well-placed and fitting music and great sound processing, combined with my Corsair Void Wireless create an amazing atmosphere at any point in the game. Eerie in caves and dark chasms, calming outside during the quite mornings, exciting during a cataclysm of some kind or when you are exploring large alient structures.Contrary to the sound, the graphics is not that great. Poor texture quality is quite common, despite running on highest settings, and my 2560x1080 monitor really highlights lack of polygons on many models. Lighting is not better than Skyrim with mods and in general this game looks like something from 2011, and no a 2016 game running on UE4. I did work with Unreal Engine 4 a while ago and I know what it can do without too much effort from the art team. I guess it simply wasn't the focus. What I will say is that weather effects do look amazing, even if the tornados for example always repeat the same animation, which is not exactly accurate (but then again this is an oceanic planet with a desert climate, so clearly realism is not what they were going for).Lastly I would like to express my disappointment at the game's ending. It is, frankly,♥♥♥♥♥♥ Absolute trash. After such an awesome game to get such a rushed, vaigue, anticlimatic and dumb ending is much worse than getting it at the end of a trash game. I don't know if they ran out of money, or if they are sequel-baiting, but that ending provided no explanation, no closure, and no answers whatsoever. Moreover, after the game spent so much effort building up the importance of your task, making the player invest in that importance (even the death screen constantly tells you about it), it is extremely disheartening to just see such abrupt and inconclusive finalie to your mission.The ending is, by far, the worst part of the game. So much so that I probably would have been better off if I just left the game at that point, where I finish the communications tower. It was even worse because I didn't expect it to be so bad. I honestly thought there's going to be some extra levels on thealien mothership, teased in the distance for the last 3 levels. Never could I have though that such a good game can just end like that.I still recommend it, because no matter how bad the ending is, the rest of the game is excellent. And all you horror devs: THIS is how you make horror. This game is not even a horror by nature, but it's scary sections are more eerie than 20 Amnesia's combined. Because instead of putting stupidly exaggerated ugly monsters and jump-scares, it manages to create an atmosphere that tickles your nerves even when you KNOW there's no danger. That is friggin impressive. So yeah: play it. And I hope by expecting a disappointing ending, you'll be less disappointed than I was, when it ended so abruptly."
76561198091381751,Recommended,313630,29213299,Posted: 12 January,all,Goky,"8/10Always have an oil torch. Your best friend. If you feel comfortable, the weather will make sure you won't for very long. Surviving in the game is difficult even without an array of creatures trying to kill you. A beautiful game with puzzles. Great story. The story line alone could carry the game. Large backstory and collectables. Pretty cool they added some fan art.Now to reason its 8/10. The animations when performing actions like cutting or breaking a wall for example. The backstory is very scattered. It takes real effort to locate all the tablets, and i did because it was worth it mind you. If you lose your oil torch it is very very hard to survive. Its almost unrealistic to survive without it. Normal torch doesn't last at all but that just my opinion.Nutural: Game was different from what I expected when i first got it. Didn't dissappoint.Its an excellent game. Best $10 game i got in years."
