76561198028702173,Recommended,313630,28138163,"Posted: 2 December, 2016",all,Galahad,"HTC Vive review.Basically Prometheus meets The Martian. Except it's a full fleshed game and not another ""experience"".I was a bit confused by the gameplay and movement at first but make no mistake, this game is a grower. Once you'll get used to the controls you will be ready to begin a brilliant Sci-Fi aventure combining exploration, discovery and survival.The sense of presence and general atmosphere are amazing. You really feel like you're alone on this forsaken alien planet.As I was exploring this astonishingly well-crafted world I kept saying to myself ""WOW"", because thanks to VR I was THERE on the top of a giant tower looking at those 2 ominous moons hanging in the sky.Despite being focused on exploration, The Solus Project offers some cool survival aspects. The weather can be harsh (rain, thunder, extreme temperatures) but that's nothing compared to the tornadoes and the meteor showers trying to kill you occasionally. Another positive note is the sound. The effects are great and the music is top notch.I found the story quite engaging and I really recommend to everyone playing this to read all the lore infos on the stone tablets scattered across the world. It really helps to understand the ending.Technically speaking, the game ran just fine on low settings (except for textures resolution on medium) with super sampling set to 130 on my GTX 780Ti.My only problem is the same as every UE4 games in VR: that goddamn aliasing. It can really be annoying and it's a shame because The Solus Project is a gorgeous game.If you love adventure, good sci-fi and own a VR headset look no further. This is the game you're looking for.Congratulations to the team who made this. I really hope to play a sequel in the future."
