76561197979348554,Not Recommended,313630,28806151,"Posted: 29 December, 2016",all,columbine,"Good: For the first few minutes you play this game you think it's really going to be amazing. You've got a standard survival scenario and a set of interesting-looking islands to explore ... the sound effects and music are good, the graphics are good, it's very promising.Bad: Then you quickly realize that what you're actually going to do is explore a set of very linear caves, occasionally puncuated by a stone tablet or obelisk in an alien language that your PDA will translate for you, and maybe a button-and-lever puzzle or some variant on that. And that's all you're going to do.I like adventure/story games. I like exploration/open world games. I even like survival games, if they're not too frustrating. This game would probably be pretty good if the people who made it had concentrated on one or even two of those things. But they seem to be determined to do all three at once, and they do a horrible job of it.Imagine if the devs had concentrated on story and puzzles and just made this a really good cave-crawl mystery. Or imagine if it was purely an ""explore, get resources, try to build what you need to get rescued"" game. Either of those would have been better than this.The story's not compelling enough and the puzzles not interesting enough for this to make a good adventure game; the exploration aspects are just ""look for secrets""; the survival aspects mostly involve your PDA nagging you to sleep what feels like every five minutes.This is doubly disappointing given that The Ball had puzzles which were actually novel and interesting. The Ball was fun to play even when I had to cheat (usually because I got tired of doing the same jumping puzzle twenty times when it was impossible to aim jumps accurately).With this game, the first time I encountered an enemy in the game who could actually kill me (in the Hallways of Darkness), I stopped and tried to decide whether it was worth 