,Recommended,313630,28985372,Posted: 3 January,all,the_real_jareth,"VR reviewI am playing this game with my VIVE for 10 hours now and think that I have finished it for about 50%. I have the latest patch installed and the game runs with perfect performance on my not-so-high-end-anymore i7 2600k/GTX 970 combination. VR support is absolutely flawless so far and the handling through the VIVE controllers works very good. The game supports two ways of movement, the well-known teleportation system and the possibility to seamlessly move over the floor in the direction you are currently looking. Although the latter method is a bit slow (i.e. the movement is a bit slow), I use it whenever possible because IMHO it offers much better immersion. So I use the teleportion system only for climbing, for which it works very well.Regarding the game itself, when I was buying the VIVE I was especially hoping for a game that puts me on an alien planet full with mysteries, ancient ruins, and fantastic surroundings. A different, exciting world for me to explore. Well, the Solus Project is nothing less than the answer to these hopes. It looks great, even phenomenal sometimes, e.g. while standing on the shoreline, watching the two moons rising above you together with the occasional falling stars, or when exploring a gigantic cave filled with ancient structures of an old civilization. And the sound is even better than the graphics, providing very intense and even scary moments regularly. By the way, I am using a 26 years old AKG K-280 Parabolic earphone and this game simply lets me believe that it must be the best earphone ever built :)I have read some complaints about this game in other reviews stating that it not difficult and complex enough. I guess this is not completely untrue. For example, in the Solus Project you must eat, drink and sleep regularly. But throughout the game you will find more food and water than you will ever need. You will even find camps (marked with a white icon directly in the world) with unlimited food and water resources regularly. Sleeping is also no problem since you can do it in most places. Interacting with the world is also not very complex. Finding a key here, repairing a lever there, and putting a stone on a plate on the ground. Nevertheless you will most probably die a few times in the game, since it contains a number of different traps, which you will simply overlook from time to time (note that your character has enough health points and will usually not die because of a single trap only).Regarding myself, I must admit that I am happy with the difficulty of the game as it is, because it gives me enough time to explore the world very thoroughly. Since the world is so beautiful this is simply more important for me than a more difficult game. And being able to finish the game all by myself without the need of a guide from the Internet is also not a bad thing, I guess.Note that each area (cave, etc.) of the game contains about ten or more secret locations, and it is a real challenge to find them. Usually the game will reward you with an upgrade to one of your stats when you find one of these secrets. So, yes, this also means that your character can improve during the game (health points, resistances).Regarding saving, the game lets you save on special obelisks that you will find along the way (often enough). Beside this, the game automatically saves when you are sleeping, which means that in fact you can save almost anytime, which is really useful when you are about to try something dangerous. Note however that the game always uses the same single savegame.To say something negative about this game at all, it took about 1-2 hours to become great. Because it started with an intro that did not even look average to me, and the first two (rather small) areas in the game didn't look especially good, either. I can promise you however that the visual appearance of the game will strongly improve after that weak beginning.Conclusion: The Solus Project is a not-to-complicated action adventure that looks and sounds so great in VR that everybody with the slightest interest in SF should play it!Update #1Four hours later and while exploring a large surface area I wanted to add that the survival aspect is more present here than in the caves before because it becomes very cold during the night. So you really have to do some planning, do the exploring during the day and seek shelter during the night, or you will freeze to death.And I also wanted to add that there is an option that controls your movement speed when not using the teleportation system, and its initial setting was only 50%. So please forget what I said about the slow movement speed!Update #2Four hours (18) more I must say that the game still gets better and also more complex. I have discovered two secret caves that I am exploring right now and they are quite challenging. They are more dark, narrow, and contain lots of crossroads so that I have started to take notes about the ways I have already explored. And food and water is very rare so that you have to be careful to find your way out early enough. Great!"
