76561198076448352,Recommended,313630,26334901,"Posted: 31 October, 2016",all,"He's dead, Jim!","The Solus Project is the first VR game I actually play. I have some other titles and demos which support VR and they are fine for testing and the ""Mhm, looks nice"" or ""Promising"" moment, but I rarely spend time in there for the game, its atmosphere and story itself. In this game VR is fun and impressive enough that I rather wear my headset and stand/walk in my room for hours than sitting in my comfy chair and look at my monitor.The VR support is done well enough, although some things are still rough. For example I wasn't able to play before switching to the release candidate branch. Sound sometimes only works when going to the desktop and focusing the game window. Saving in the wrong place can corrupt the save (will load in a black room). There are also some things I don't like much, like teleporting. It's feels a bit immersion breaking, just changing the place from one frame to the next, but normal walking isn't really an option due to VR sickness risks. None of those are showstoppers however and don't prevent me from enjoying the game in VR for several hours per session.Aside from VR I like where the game and story is going so far, but then I do like the genre (Explore/Adventure/Walking Simulator) a lot in the first place. If you do to and if you have a Vive, then this game is a safe pick for a very fair price.As performance, I have a GTX 1070 on a i5 3570K and play with Medium Quality settings."
