,Recommended,313630,28983468,Posted: 3 January,all,Morgue,"I came into this game with pretty high expectations, and while it did fall short of a couple, it alsoexceededa couple, and easily met the rest, which in my opinion evens out very nicely.First of all, I highly recommend playing The Ball first. You can buy them together in a bundle for fairly cheap, and the games really are connected. I won't say how or why, that's a massive spoiler. You can absolute enjoy The Solus Project without ever having played The Ball, but it definitely improves the experience.Yes, this is an adventure/survival game, but the degree to which the survival aspect impacts your ability to explore is pretty much your choice. You can turn the difficulty right down to nothing, turn on item hints, and basically transform the game into a survival-lite walking simulator in order to enjoy the story. Or, you can throw the difficulty as high as it will go and spend 90% of your time stressing about where your next meal is coming from, and does that look like a thundercloud? Your choice.It's quite story-heavy, but you get to work through it at near enough your own pace. You'll probably feel rushed because of the pace of certain events, or because you need to find X resource before you die from lack of it, but even then you can backtrack to find whatever story elements you missed later on. There are also collectibles to find, which actually give you a small buff to your various survival stats.There are a couple of annoying bugs, but the devs are still working on playability patches so I expect they'll be fixed eventually. I'll amend this review when that happens. Unless you get yourself in the incredibly unique situation I did, the bugs shouldn't impede your progress in any way. They're just an irritation.Ilovedthis game, and I know for a fact that I'm going to be replaying it soon."
