,Recommended,313630,22279691,"Posted: 6 April, 2016",all,[AoR] Genolune,"Normally I play a lot of Bethesda games for their large mod database on the internet and I can go ham and not worry about ""immersion"", so I picked up the Solus Project for a different kind of experience.  If you've played Myst, it's a lot like that combined with a Metroidvania travel here and do this, and go there and get this object type playstyle.  I played it on easy mode until I ran out of the story (it’s still being released a bit at a time because it is Early Access), but on the harder difficulties you can get your fill of survival.  Temperature and wetness contribute to potential hypothermia as well as varying weather such as sunny weather, snow, rain, meteor showers, and tornadoes.  There are also plenty of secret areas to get items that boost your resistance to hypothermia, increase movement speed, etc. and you are guarenteed not to find all of them in the first go.There is a story here about Gliese as well as plenty of notes to find and read about your mission and fellow Solus Project astronauts and trying to communicate about your crash landing.  Go to the spoiler tag to reveal what I've uncovered and think of the story.From the in game texts strewn about on monuments and such it seems that a race of coneheaded people were taken from their planet by much taller humanoids which they named Sky Ones (because these aliens came in spaceships.)  These Sky Ones showed them how to make stone buildings and other sciences.  But there is a sinister element here.  The Sky Ones are underground dwellers.  The coneheaded children are sent to an underground monastery to participate in a ritual called the Flameless Rite, which if I understand the pictures and stone tablets correctly essentially involves running around with a torch that attracts a creature of some sort that is smoke, spikes and rays of light (you don’t actually see what the creature is inside the smoke) which then eats the child and flame.  I can only guess but what I gathered is that lots of coneheads are sacrificed to these “dark spirits” as they call them to power them up and the “dark spirit” is used by the Sky Ones to power their machines or for some other reason.  Of course all of this is done under the guise of some religion so the general conehead populace doesn’t realize they are food, leading to some wise rebels wanting to expel these superficially kind but sinister Sky Ones from their world.  As part of the main story you follow a giant cable from the surface to underground and manage to activate it using a tower which doubles as a lightning rod that funnels the energy.  Overall, it becomes kind of a horror atmospheric game without really meaning to at times.I recommend it for a change of pace and because it’ll leave you wanting to find out about what happened on Gliese as well as the Solus Project itself."
