76561197975951483,Recommended,313630,26295078,"Posted: 29 October, 2016",all,TG ABRA,"""You dawg, I heard you like secrets so I secreted a secret into your secret.""A survival genre game with a definite classic adventure game feel where the thrills are 100% exploration.The Solus Project's high quality aestetics and richly drawn storyline are a welcome change after playing a string of unpolished Early Access survival games, There is zero base-building or environmental alteration. But you do feel a sense of home in a cave or piece of wreckage that you cache found supplies in that you repeatedly use as shelter for a few nights before moving on. This sense of home is more vibrant than a home base you made yourself. When the environment offers you shelter, it has a sense of being a nurturing Other rather than a constructed base that is an extension of Self. It's hard to explain but it is art at its best.Likewise, the story is 'discovered' as you explore in the form of found ship's logs and ruins rather than being thrust upon you via scripted events, quests, or NPC dialogue. This creates suspense in the same way as characters in a scary movie wandering a creepy basement stumble upon a cursed book.  It makes the player feel as though they are accompanying their character on the adventure rather than in other games where you control and direct the character in a procedural sandbox.Just an exquite game that slowly reveals its many secrets at a delicious pace that allows you to savor the plot as your capacity to survive allows you to explore the world around you more fully before you seek shelter in a storm or at nightfall.A must-buy for any fan of sandbox survival games who have forgotten how satisfying a constructed survival game can be when you aren't distracted by sand castle building in a meaningless procedural world (and I love games like that)."
