76561197978820568,Recommended,313630,23608263,"Posted: 16 June, 2016",all,<AR> Madcat,"Let's start off with some backstory, just to be clear...When I was 8, the first Unreal game released. Not Unreal Tournament, no... Unreal Gold Edition with Return to Na'Pali. A campaign game, very shooter focused but also many RPG elements. Prior to Unreal Gold, my experience with gaming was purely simulators, mostly flight combat. I never owned a console, never experienced Zelda, but that game sold me on a genre I never knew existed. I completed the campaign and the expansion 4 times before downloading any modpack mini campaign I could find and playing those, too. Since then many games have released that had RPG elements which I've enjoyed. The newer Tomb Raiders, Fallout series, Elder Scrolls. I've loved them all, but none as passionately as that first, little-known game that truly taught me how epic a story a videogame could convey.Flash forward 18 years. I happen to be browsing Steam when a game pops up that seems to have some interest. ""Okay"" I say, as I watch the trailer like many before. ""I'll give it a try, why not it looks entertaining""I had no idea what I was getting.I think the first hint was probably the crosses with the aliens everywhere. Not simple crosses, no... crosses for aliens with 4 arms. But why, when these aliens all have 2? Where had I seen such crosses before? Could it possibly be? Nali?Enter aliens. ""Wait, is that a Skaarj?"" ""No but damn that's similar, and the staff reminds me an awful lot of the Krall..."" Then I start thinking about the plot. A technologically advanced mysterious alien race which subjugates a physically more frail other alien race that is still primitive in development, and uses their technology like magic? Well okay, also familiar... At least they don't have to mine Tarydium.So I complete the game, hyped up and craving more, but also still curious about these glaring similarities... Come to find out in an interview the developer seems to share the same passion I do for a little known old game...Overall, I thought the added survival elements really helped modernize it over the inspiration. They are well balanced if you know what you are doing, and select the correct level of difficulty for your preferred playstyle. The added spookiness over UG was unexpected but welcome, and never quite the jump scare most people go for, but a more subtle reaction in the gut. Walking up to a corpse, seeing it lean upright and stare up at me as I stand next to it... I didn't jump back but had to utter aloud ""Ohhhh no you did not just do that...""Honestly, the only thing I think this game is missing is an ASMD...Needless to say, I'll be raving about this one to friends for a while yet. The moment I get my Vive there will be a second playthrough happening."
