76561198093731118,Recommended,313630,28791945,"Posted: 29 December, 2016",all,harbinsky.m.e,"This is a weird game to actually write a review based solely on the binary “thumbs up” or “thumbs down” dynamic.I decided to try this based on the teaser/trailer the company put out for the game. The idea of being alone on an alien world; the weather, humidity, temperature, hunger, thirst, and the wind effecting your survival seed like a rather neat play dynamic. Oddly enough, it worked rather well. True, you’re viewing all that through your PDA that looks for all intents like a cell phone from 2010, but it works rather effectively.The set pieces were rather well constructed for the most part, and the lead up to the alien civilization’s eventual demise worked rather well. I can overlook the immortal alien food and stew that you keep finding later on because you need to keep from starving somehow. Also the torch and flask of oil that never get used up is a bit jarring considering I was carrying around a bunch of stuff I didn't need for a while befire figuring that out. I can even live with the alien language being just a simple replace cypher. For the most part it was visually stunning, a decent play mechanic, and it held me in for most of it.Until it kind of didn’t.Here’s the thing. From a non-spoiler aspect, the protagonist is kind of an idiot. I understand the idea of having the character keep a voce log to spoon feed the player the bits that they might not be picking up on, but honestly it kind of took me out of the environment every time they talked, epically toward the end when they were just coming up with ideas that were dead wrong for the express purpose of getting you to the point in the plot that the writers wanted to have the game go to.Which is fine, if you want us to go there; just the more subtle approach might work a little better.Spoilers next.Also the “bad” aliens are still alive. You don’t actually fight them, but having them leave you notes, seeing them wander about, and calling you on the radio telling you what to do is…….well……unnecessary.The scene with the dolls though. That was quite well done.It almost makes up for the 3 liter bottle of champagne that never runs dry that you find towards the end.Almost."
