,Not Recommended,313630,29103950,Posted: 7 January,all,Kryyss,"Goldfish. Yup, you're reading that right. Goldfish. Apparently, they have memories which only last a matter of seconds. How someone figured that out I have no idea. Perhaps someone taught the fish morse-code or two-bubbles for 'yes' and one for 'no' but anyway. They're lucky really. You stick them into a bowl around a foot wide, put in some rocks and a castle and they'll find it endlessly exciting. ""Ooh, rocks! Never seen that before!."" ""Ooh a castle! Never seen that before!"" ""Ohh rocks! never seen that before!"" Repeat ad infinitum.Goldfish would love Solus Project. If they had fingers... and could remember the controls long enough to use them.At first Solus Project appears to have it all. Great atmosphere, interesting scenery, a mysterious planet and spectacular environmental effects which vary from tidal patterns and dynamic weather to tornados and meteor showers. It's a walking simulator with some survival elements thrown in to keep things interesting... or at least, it attempts to. Just for a moment, go look at the screenshots. Now understand that what you see there is what you'll be looking at for the rest of the game. The first island looks like the second, the caves look the same, the alien ruins look the same. It's that goldfish in the bowl but you don't have the ability to forget that what you see 10hrs into the game is largely the same as what you saw in the first hour.When you look at the game, you may think that this is an open world. It isn't, it's a linear environment that ironically loops back upon itself. So not only is it repetitive, it also makes the player retread through areas they already visited. The level design of the game itself also has a number of issues. The translocator teleportation device is intended to allow you to traverse the landscape more easily but handles really poorly. It's like throwing a metal cooking tray with all of the dead weight you would expect but then, almost paradoxically, it bounces off of surfaces like it was made of rubber. Worse still is the fact that it can come to a stop on an angled surface that is actually too steep for the player to stand on, so when you teleport to it you slide down. There are also numerous instances where the translocator will allow you to teleport into a space where you are trapped. This frequently happens with the pentagon shaped pillars you see the developers have reused again and again throughout the environments. When trapped by the world geometry in this way your only option is to quit out and load up your last save game. As you can imagine, this deters a player from exploring which works contrary to the point of the game.As the developers themselves have said, it is the players fault if they get themselves into 'bad spots' and not their responsibility to build the world to prevent these problems as any attempt to do so would be ""even more immersion breaking"". So no doubt there are many more ways for the player to get stuck, break progression by going off the intended route or get trapped in world geometry throughout the game because the devs feel that it is better for players to get stuck and have to reload their last save point or use the command console to fix the problem than to fix issues with the game.It also appears that the world is also ""quite similar visually by design"" which they feel excuses why it feels repetitive.All in all, Solus Project is far from worth picking up even on sale. A lot of effort has gone into the games atmosphere but there just isn't anything to make it interesting to play after the first couple of hours. Hunting around for secret caves and bonuses which give 1% to a stat is also really poor design as the reward does not justify trudging around the intentionally repetative environments shining your torch into every dark corner to see if there is something tucked away off the clearly established route to the next area,I really wanted to enjoy the Solus Project - but saddly I'd need to be a goldish to do that.(edit - updated middle of review to reflect the fact that the devs did not intend to create platforming sections although they exist and that Wrenchse (a developer) has stated that the problems with level design ""might mean that people get themselves into bad spots"" but that ""we do think that is more preferable than having invisible boxes blocking stuff off"".)"
