,Not Recommended,313630,23528882,"Posted: 12 June, 2016",all,pechy,"Disclaimer: This review is only based on the first 2-3 hours of gameplay.The Solus Project markets itself as an immersive survival/exploration game. Unfortunately it's hard to be immersed when you're bored waiting for a game to get good.The survival gameplay initially seems promising, tracking your health, water, calories, body temperature and fatigue, as well as the environmental temperature, humidity and windspeed, on a PDA that slides into view when you look down (I imagine this is a nice effect in VR - I played on a standard PC). You have an inventory to manage, prioritising food, refillable water containers and medkits. You construct a rudimentary torch from debris, stock up on supplies, and are ready to explore the nearby cave system. Unfortunately I quickly realise there's always plenty of food and water available (even underground) so managing hunger and thirst quickly becomes a chore. In the week or so of in-game time that has passed by torch (a bit of oil and kindling on a metal rod) has never gone out. The only stat I found myself paying attention to was the temperature. This boils down to using the torch if it's cold and using another light source (flashlight, crystal, glowstick) if it's hot. This game appears to be a walking simulator with survival aspects tacked on. Unfortunately, survival is not tense or difficult, just tedious and boring.Ok, so it's not really a survival game. That's ok, there should still be plenty of fun to be had from freely exploring, without having to worry about dying of thirst, right? Well, the level design itself is fairly linear. Sometimes there are a few different branches you can take from A to B. The main incentive to explore is to discover secrets. These are basically objects that give you a minor stat increase. Only, surviving is basically just a distraction and a chore and the secrets don't contribute anything to the plot, so searching for them is just another chore in itself. Additionally, the areas are often fairly open with lots of nooks and crannies. It just isn't my idea of fun to wander around the edge of a map looking for the opening, or spending hours jumping on rocks to see if I can climb up (you usually can't).""Oh well, maybe I'm trying to make too much of this game. Let's just get immersed in the story and the visuals and get lost in this world."" I gave up on this when I realised how much of the plot relied on 'scattered notes'. When you find a piece of paper on the ground that starts with 'Yuri's Diary - 1/24' you realise you'll spend the next 10 minutes following these breadcrumbs and just hoping you don't miss any or read them out of order. The text doesn't appear all at once, it appears as if someone is typing. Accidentally move your mouse off the note and you have to start again. It is infuriating.One time, I left an indoor campsite, crouched through a crawlspace, walked through a cave, and came outside only to discover it was like 50 degrees and I was going to get hyperthermia if I stayed outside. I had to backtrack all the way to the campsite just so I could rest until evening. Not only is survival tedious, it's actually actively hindering your progress. This would be fine if it created a challenge, but it just creates more tedium.On the upside, the visuals are quite nice (if a little samey) and I feel like if I had stuck with it the plot might have picked up steam. The major problem is this game doesn't know what it wants to be. The survival gameplay, the exploration and level design, and the plot delivery are entirely at odds with each other. They contantly try and pull you in different directions making for a very tiresome experience."
