76561197987527539,Not Recommended,313630,23543960,"Posted: 13 June, 2016",all,Indrigis,"The road to hell is paved with good intentions. Very crudely, in this case.The Solus Project is a lazy effort that fails at being even a decent game, not to mention a good story-driven survival game.Survival: Food and water are plentiful, the torch you build within ten minutes of starting the game is permanent as it never runs out of fuel and gves you heat and light for the entire game. The torch can be extinguished if you dive into water while holding it but if it's in yout inventory, it's completely safe. Being frozen is a real danger unless you wisely choose to nap for 10 hours so it's +30 degrees outside, rendering the soaked/frozen part moot.Puzzles: They are not. The extent of puzzles is ""Press a button"", ""Put a rock onto a button"" and ""Throw the teleporter disk into a narrow opening"".General design: It's an Unreal fanfic, and a mediocre at that. Everything reminds of Na-Pali, including the two races, crucifixes made for a four-armed victim (although race C7 has two arms) and the ""stone tablets translated by your PDA"" plot delivery. It's also clearly visible that the map designer simply loves cloning hexagonal pillars with the same size and texture.Plot: It's seriously bad. Firstly, the entirety of the game is ""gather parts for a radio tower to phone home"" with no deeper reasoning and, more importantly, all the writings on the stone tablets that you decipher have no influence on the protagonist's actions even if they... REALLY should. And there's no intrigue whatsoever. The voice acting from the radio operator is quite good, though.Exploration: You don't need to. The only really useful items are the backpacks that allow you to hoard more stuff, but you don't need most of the ""very rare"" items. On the other hand, in a few places the game devolves into Item Quest. Because the only way to break weak stone walls is a mighty hammer, useful only for breaking weak stone walls and taking up inventory space otherwise.So: Bad design, an excuse plot, poor puzzles, a poor survival mechanic and, ultimately, confusing and needless lore. Good intentions, bad paving."
