,Not Recommended,313630,23446841,"Posted: 7 June, 2016",all,AzureanStudios,"Restarting my review because I made a rookie mistake: I played Hardcore Mode right from the start. That's because I was expecting a hardcore, sci-fi survival experience mixed with discoveries that felt rewarding, and intuitive enough of UI, UX, story and gameplay to get me through the game, even on hardcore mode. (""Hardcore"" after all, refers to ease of survival, not intuitive player gating, progression, quest & waypoint systems, and puzzle hints)What I got instead was a handful of deaths, and I never once figured out how to get out of the ""starting area"" (again, in Hardcore Mode)—so this is my fault, and I should dial back a bit on my criticism of the game. I'm sure if I played an easier mode I would have had more guidance.But what *still* troubles me is finding out that *spoiler alert* --------------------> the starting area isn't what the whole game is like. That's, I guess, why I was jumping around on basalt columns. I thought it was an open-world experience that was meant to continue on the other, nearby islands as I continued to discover beautiful shrines and etc. Instead, apparently, the cave is pretty much where you *have to* go to get anywhere, and apparently the cave leads to nothing but more cave-ness.Imagine playing Skyrim, but by the time you get to the first ""dungeon"" of the game, you never go back out into the outer world to continue exploring. That's how the Solus Project feels (as of yet), and that's why I asked for my money back. I paid half the price of Skyrim for what I thought would be an indie, sci-fi, survival/suspense version of ""half the game"", so to speak, but that is definitely not what I got.I think I was jumping around on basalt columns because I was hoping that WOULD cause me to get somewhere and make progress in the outside, survival-world. Maybe the developer should implement that, because according to most reviews, once you enter the ""main cave tunnel"", the whole survival element goes out the window.Why not expand on the outside world, and put some fallen ships with treasure in them at the top of a path of basalt columns? That would be a much more rewarding dynamic than what people are finding in the game as it is.I still want my money back for this game, but I don't hate it. A lot about it was very good, but it was *not* a final release for VR or for PC, and it should therefore not (yet) be sold at the price it is sold at, unless it's declared an early-access price. I found plenty of bugs and so have many others.This game needs more time in the oven for VR development and more focus testing for the PC version. I will keep an eye on it and re-purchase down the line if it is A) sold for the price of an ""unfinished experience"" or B) brought up to the standards of a true $20 ""final game"" in the survival game category."
